//Same Tree//
//Given the roots of two binary trees p and q, write a function to check if they are the same or not.
//Two binary trees are considered the same if they are structurally identical, and the nodes have the same value.
//Example 1:
//Input: p = [1,2,3], q = [1,2,3]
//Output: true
//Example 2:
//Input: p = [1,2], q = [1,null,2]
//Output: false
//Example 3:
//Input: p = [1,2,1], q = [1,1,2]
//Output: false

Brute force approach -> (It is recursive but not memory efficient)

class Solution {
public:
    void preorder(TreeNode* root, vector<string>& nodes) {         //TreeNode* root -- Current node being visited. vector<string>& nodes --- Pass the vector by reference so we can add values directly to it.
        if(root == nullptr) {                                      // For ex- 1    , Here root->left of node 2 is null.
                                                                             /
                                                                            2 
            nodes.push_back("null");
            return;
        }
        nodes.push_back(to_string(root->val));
        preorder(root->left, nodes);
        preorder(root->right, nodes);
    }
    bool isSameTree(TreeNode* p, TreeNode* q) {
        vector<string> tree1;
        vector<string> tree2;
        preorder(p, tree1);
        preorder(q, tree2);
        return tree1 == tree2;
    }
};



Example -  
    1                                                 1
   /                                                   \
  2                                                     2
["1","2","null","null","null"] , ["1","null","2","null","null"] 

*******So not equal, we include null values because without them our brute force approach won't work for cases like these.*******

Complexity Analysis
Time Complexity -> O(n)
Space Complexity -> O(n)


Optimal Approach -> (This is also recursive but instead of building vectors, it compares nodes directly)

class Solution {
public:
    bool isSameTree(TreeNode* p, TreeNode* q) {
        if(p == nullptr && q == nullptr) {              //If both nodes are null, they match, so return true.
            return true;
        }
        if(p == nullptr || q == nullptr) {             // If exactly one node is null and the other isn't, the trees differ, so return false. 
            return false;
        }
        if(p->val != q->val) {                         //If values dont match, return false
            return false;
        }
        return isSameTree(p->left, q->left)               //Comparing left and right corresponding nodes of both trees recursively, returns true only if both statements are true, false otherwise.
            && isSameTree(p->right, q->right);
    }
};

Complexity Analysis
Time Complexity -> O(n)
Space Complexity -> O(h)
where:
h = height of tree


Corner Cases
1. Both Trees Empty
p = []
q = []

Output:
true

2. One Tree Empty
p = []
q = [1]

Output:
false

3. Same Structure, Same Values
    1          1
   / \        / \
  2   3      2   3

Output:
